0.header:
Looking at a possible injury to the ligaments that connect bones to one another.

This injury can cause damage to the ligaments and surrounding tissues leading to swelling, inflammation, and bruising around the ankle.



Let's see if it is something to seek urgent care for or something you can take care of on our own.

1.header: Do you have severe pain even when NOT putting your weight on it?

2.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Looking at serious inflammation going on.

3.header: Can you hear a popping sound coming from the ankle area when you try to move?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at a dislocation

5.header: Looking at the ankle joint, would you say it looks deformed?

6.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Will need complete evaluation

7.header: Can you even put any weight on this ankle?

8.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • May be dislocated or seriously inflammed.

9.header: Were you able to use the ankle immediately after the sprain?

10.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need professional evaluation

11.header:
Those were some of the reasons to seek urgent care for an ankle sprain.

21.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

32.header:

61.title: Athlete's foot
dlg:
This foot fungal infection range from mild to severe, may last a short or long time and may persist or recur from time to time, but they generally respond well to treatment.

Long-term medication and preventive measures may be needed.

0.header:
Athlete's foot is a fungal infection of the foot.

Let's see what we are looking at before a pharmacist recommend something over-the-counter.

1.header:
Are you looking at athlete's foot in the first place?
Let's find out.

We have to be sure it is not some kind of reaction to something you may be allergic to in your shoes or socks.

2.header: Are you experiencing itching between your toes or side of the foot?

4.header: Is the affected area cracked?

6.header: Is the area peeling?

8.header: Does the affected area have scaling borders?

9.header:
Yes?
More than likely looking at athlete's foot.

10.header: Alright. Is this affected area red?

12.header:
Is the area burning?

Or stinging?

13.header:
Yes?
May be looking at athlete's foot.

Suspect athlete's foot if the affected area is:

  • Red
  • Itchy and peeling
  • Burning
  • Itchy and cracked

14.header:
Any blisters that are oozing?

Or crusty?

15.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Athlete's foot is getting very bad.
  • May be looking at a mixed infection.

16.header: Does the area look eroded?

17.header:
Yes?
This is getting bad.

Let's see if you have to see a doctor urgently.

18.header: Any exposed raw tissues?

19.header:
Yes?
Athlete's foot is getting bad.

Let's see if we have to see a doctor urgently.

20.header:
A,
Those were signs and symptons of athlete's foot.

If you're still thinking athlete's foot, let's see if you have to see a doctor right away.

Or if you can take care of this with over-the-counter measures.

30.header:
Is the affected area swollen?

Warm to touch?

31.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Secondary bacterial infection, cellulitis, and lymphangitis are common complications

32.header: Any red streaks in the affected area?

33.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a mixed infection
  • Secondary bacterial infection, cellulitis, and lymphangitis are common complications.

34.header: Any kind of pus or drainage?

35.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a bacterial infection mixed in.

36.header: Do you also have fever with this athletes foot?

37.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at something more serious.

38.header: What about blisters in the hands, arms or chest?

39.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible bacteria infection.

40.header: Are you diabetic?

41.header:
Call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Will need prescription cream or pills
  • Going to be hard to treat.

42.header: Do you have a weakened immune system?

43.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Will be hard to treat
  • Complications with self treatment is high.

44.header: Is this the third case in a few months?

45.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Over the counter medication is not going to cut this.

46.header:
A,
If not directed to see a doctor, we will assume a mild case going forward.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use to take care of the athlete's foot that is available over-the-counter.

Or do you think you should seek urgent care from the discussions so far?

0.header:
Heel pain when you stand up first time in the morning, may signal plantar fasciitis.

There are other causes of foot pain. Let's see what you are looking at before deciding how to take care if this.

1.header:
A,
Is the foot pain due to inflammation of the plantar fascia or something else?

First, we will start by eliminating serious causes of leg or foot pain that will require urgent or emergency care.

2.header:
Do you have foot pain that became severe within seconds or minutes?

Particularly if you have a history of heart problems.

3.header:
Seek emergency room or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You might be looking at something serious like an embolism of one of the arteries that supply blood to the foot.
  • Especially so if your foot feels cool.

4.header:
Is your toe, foot or ankle warm to touch, red and painful?

Or very tender?
(covering it with blanket hurts.)

5.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at an acute attack of gout.
  • The pain starts suddenly, often during the night and is often described as throbbing, crushing, or excruciating.

6.header:
Does the foot feel numb, burning , tingling?

Like a deep pain in there?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at peripheral neuropathy involving the legs.
  • Must see the doctor if you are diabetic.

8.header:
Are the feet and toes swollen, feeling numb?

Painful at the ankle and heel?

9.header:
Call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at hypothyroidism.

10.header:
When you take off your shoes, do you feel a throbbing heel pain?

With heel puffy and warm?

11.header:
See a doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possibly calcaneal bursitis.

12.header:
Alright.
Those were to rule out other serious causes of foot or leg pain.

Now, let's see if you are looking at Plantar fasciitis.

20.header: Is the foot pain like a knife or a pin sticking into the bottom of the foot?

22.header: Does it feel like the bottom of the feet is burning?

24.header: Does it ache when you put weight on it?

25.header:
Yes?
We are thinking plantar fasciitis.

With plantar fasciitis you will experience:

  • Foot pain like a knife or a pin sticking into the bottom of the foot.
  • Like the bottom of the feet is burning
  • Ache when bearing weight.

26.header:
Is the pain worse when you first rise in the morning?

Pain gets better after 5 to 10 min, only to return later in the day.

27.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of plantar fasciitis.

Plantar fasciitis symptoms include:

  • Foot pain like a knife or a pin sticking into the bottom of the foot.
  • Like the bottom of the feet is burning
  • Aching when bearing weight.
  • Pain worse when you first arise in the morning.

28.header: When pushing off of the heel, does the pain get worse?

29.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of plantar fasciitis.

With plantar fasciitis you will experience:

  • Foot pain like a knife or a pin sticking into the bottom of the foot.
  • Like the bottom of the feet is burning
  • Aching when bearing weight.
  • Pain worse when you first arise in the morning.
  • Worse when you push off of the heel.

30.header:
When you sit down for awhile and then stand up again...

...does the pain get worse?

31.header:
Yes?
This usually occur with plantar fasciitis.

Symptoms include:

  • Foot pain like a knife or a pin sticking into the bottom of the foot.
  • Like the bottom of the feet is burning
  • Aching when bearing weight.
  • Pain worse when you first arise in the morning.
  • Worse when you push off of the heel.
  • Pain worse when you stand up after sitting down for a length of time

32.header: Does the pain get worse when you climb the stairs?

33.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of plantar fasciitis.

With plantar fasciitis, the pain will get worse when you:

  • First arise in the morning
  • Push off of the heel
  • Climb stairs

34.header: Does standing for a while make the pain become more like a dull ache?

35.header:
Yes?
This happens often with plantar fasciitis.

36.header:
A,
Those were symptoms of plantar fasciitis.

If you think it is what you are looking at, let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use that is available over-the-counter.

Or would you like to seek urgent care?

63.title: Arthritis
dlg: A rubbery tissue called cartilage cushions your bones at the joints and allows gliding of the bones. If it wears down, the bones rub together, cushioning is decreased or eliminated leading to pain, swelling and stiffness.

0.header:
Arthritis is inflammation of one or more of the joints.

There are many types of arthritis. We will discuss the most common type called osteoarthritis, which is due to wear and tear on the joints and aging.


Let's see if you have arthritis anyway and not just a muscle sprain or minor joint pain before you see what is available for arthritis over-the-counter.

1.header: Is the affected joint very painful?

3.header: Is the joint getting stiff?

4.header:
No?
Hmmm. You may NOT be looking at arthtitis then.

It may just be a form of joint sprain. Anyway, let's continue and see what you can uncover.

5.header: Is the pain like a deep ache that gets worse on waking up in the morning?

6.header:
No?
The earliest symptom with arthritis is a deep aching pain worse on waking up.

Arthritis usually invlove:

  • Joints that get stiff
  • Deep aching pain
  • Gets worse on waking up in the morning

7.header: Does the pain get worse when you put weight or pressure on the affected joint?

8.header:
No?
A symptom of arthritis is pain worse with weight or pressure on the joint.

Arthritis usually invlove:

  • Joints that gets stiff
  • Deep aching pain
  • Gets worse on waking up in the morning
  • Pain worse with weight or pressure on the joint

9.header: Does it get worse after you exercise?

10.header:
No?
It doesn't get worse after exercising?

Arthritis usually invlove:

  • Joints that gets stiff
  • Deep aching pain
  • Gets worse on waking up in the morning
  • Pain worse with weight or pressure on the joint
  • Pain worse after exercise

11.header: When you wake up in the morning, does the joint get stiff?

12.header:
Yes?
Most likely looking at arthritis in this case.

Stiffness follows waking up or inactivity but lasts less than 30 min and lessens when you start moving about.

Let's see if you need to see a doctor for this arthritis before we send you to the pharmacist to recommend something for you to take that is over-the-counter.

You will invariably have to see a doctor for diagnosis. This is usually by x-ray.

13.header:
Any rubbing, grating, or crackling sound...

With movement of the joint?

14.header:
Yes?
More than likely looking at arthritis.

Usually with arthritis there is rubbing, grating, or crackling sound with movement of the joint that is affected.

15.header:
Press the affected joint area.

Does it feel tender?

16.header:
Yes?
More than likely looking at arthtitis.

Let's see if you need to see a doctor for this arthritis right away before we see what a pharmacist recommend you take over-the-counter.

17.header:
A,
Hope you have an idea if you are looking at arthitis or not by now.

Suspect arthritis if:

  • Joints that gets stiff
  • Deep aching pain
  • Pain worse on waking up in the morning
  • Pain worse with weight or pressure on the joint
  • Pain worse after exercise

Let's see if you need to see a doctor urgently for this suspected arthritis before using over-the-counter measures.

Note that you still have to see a doctor for proper diagnosis.

Diagnosis is by x-rays.
An x-ray of affected joints will show a loss of the joint space. In advanced cases, there will be a wearing down of the ends of the bone and bone spurs.

20.header:
First, how soon do you need to see a doctor?
It will get worse over time.

The goal is to control it and hopefully reduce the need for surgery as long as possible.

21.header: Is the affected joint swollen?

23.header: Is it tender when pressed?

25.header: Would you say you are experiencing range of motion that is very limited?

26.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Over the counter medications is not going to cut this.
  • Looking at severe case of arthitis

27.header: Does the pain wake you up at night?

28.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need complete evaluation

29.header: Are the symptoms getting worse by the day?

31.header: Are you experiencing decreased ability to perform your usual everyday activities?

32.header:
Yes?
Time to see a doctor.

Here is why:

  • It is going to get worse
  • Need complete evaluation

33.header:
A,
If you think you have arthritis, you would need to see a doctor.

There are different types of arthritis.

For now, let's get an over-the-counter pharmacist's recommendation to help with this.
